  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My girlfriend for 4years cheated 3 times. I found out 2 month ago. She started talking to a guy as a friend. He called her babe, what should I do?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're going through this difficult situation. Dealing with infidelity and trust issues in a long-term relationship can be incredibly challenging and emotionally draining. Here are some steps and considerations that might help you navigate this situation:\n\n1. **Take Time to Reflect:**\n   - **Assess Your Feelings:** Before making any decisions, take some time to understand your own emotions. Are you feeling hurt, angry, confused, or a combination of these?\n   - **Evaluate the Relationship:** Consider the overall health of your relationship. Think about the positive aspects as well as the repeated instances of infidelity.\n\n2. **Communicate Openly:**\n   - **Have an Honest Conversation:** Share your feelings with your girlfriend. Express how her actions have affected you and discuss the current situation regarding her talking to another guy.\n   - **Set Clear Boundaries:** If you decide to continue the relationship, establish what is acceptable and what is not. Clear boundaries can help rebuild trust.\n\n3. **Seek Professional Help:**\n   - **Therapy or Counseling:** A professional therapist can provide a neutral space for both of you to express your feelings and work through the issues. Individual therapy can also help you process your emotions.\n   - **Couples Counseling:** If both of you are willing, couples therapy can address the underlying problems in the relationship and work towards healing.\n\n4. **Consider Your Well-Being:**\n   - **Emotional Health:** Prioritize your mental and emotional well-being. If the relationship is causing you significant distress, it might be necessary to consider stepping away.\n   - **Support System:** Lean on friends, family, or support groups for emotional support during this time.\n\n5. **Assess Her Actions:**\n   - **Patterns of Behavior:** Repeated infidelity suggests deeper issues. Consider whether she is genuinely remorseful and committed to changing her behavior.\n   - **Trust Restoration:** Rebuilding trust takes time and consistent effort. Reflect on whether you're both willing and able to work towards this.\n\n6. **Evaluate the New Situation:**\n   - **Friendship Dynamics:** Understand the nature of her friendship with the new guy. Is it purely platonic, or is there a possibility of it escalating further?\n   - **Your Comfort Level:** If her interactions with him make you uncomfortable, communicate this to her and discuss how to address it together.\n\n7. **Decide on the Future:**\n   - **Stay Together:** If you choose to continue the relationship, ensure that both of you are committed to making positive changes and rebuilding trust.\n   - **Part Ways:** If you feel that the relationship is no longer healthy or that trust cannot be rebuilt, it might be best to end the relationship for your own well-being.\n\n8. **Self-Care:**\n   - **Engage in Activities You Enjoy:** Focus on hobbies, exercise, or other activities that bring you joy and reduce stress.\n   - **Mindfulness and Relaxation:** Practices like meditation, yoga, or deep-breathing exercises can help manage emotional turmoil.\n\nRemember, you deserve to be in a relationship where you feel respected, valued, and secure. Take the time you need to make the decision that's best for your emotional health and future happiness. If you're struggling to cope, reaching out to a mental health professional can provide additional support and guidance.",
